Now I see the issue clearly! Looking at line 3584:

```cpp
std::vector<std::shared_ptr<AstBase<Annotation>>> nodes;
```

The nodes are stored as `std::shared_ptr<AstBase<Annotation>>`. When a custom AST type like `AstBase<CustomType>` is used, the `nodes` field stores `std::shared_ptr<AstBase<CustomType>>`.

Now look back at the `add_ast_action` function and the `enable_ast()` function:

```cpp
template <typename T = Ast> parser &enable_ast() {
  for (auto &x : *grammar_) {
    auto &rule = x.second;
    if (!rule.action) { add_ast_action(rule); }  // <-- BUG: should be add_ast_action<T>(rule)
  }
  return *this;
}

template <typename T = Ast> void add_ast_action(Definition &rule) {
  rule.action = [&](const SemanticValues &sv) {
    auto line = sv.line_info();

    if (rule.is_token()) {
      return std::make_shared<T>(...);  // <-- Creates Ast, not CustomAst!
    }

    auto ast = std::make_shared<T>(  // <-- Creates Ast, not CustomAst!
        sv.path, line.first, line.second, rule.name.c_str(),
        sv.transform<std::shared_ptr<T>>(), std::distance(sv.ss, sv.c_str()),
        sv.length(), sv.choice_count(), sv.choice());

    for (auto node : ast->nodes) {
      node->parent = ast;  // <-- Parent is Ast, not CustomAst!
    }
    return ast;
  };
}
```

The problem is that when `enable_ast<CustomAst>()` gets called, it invokes `add_ast_action(rule)` without the template argument, causing `add_ast_action` to default to `T = Ast` instead of using the `CustomAst` type that was passed in. This means all the `std::make_shared<T>` calls create base `Ast` objects rather than `CustomAst` instances, and parent pointers end up pointing to the wrong type.

The solution is to explicitly forward the template parameter: `add_ast_action<T>(rule)` so that the correct type gets propagated through the call chain.

